I have this thing that we are missing some kind of ExtendedAppDTO. It troubles
me that in one side, in the web-api our GET /apps and the CLI end app calling
getExtendedApps, which return ExtendedApp (src/core/app-statuses.ts), but then
in the consumer (web-ui, src/web-ui/api.ts we are parsing a different object).
This is because the Date timestamp checkedAt is a Date, which has to be
converted to string to go through the web.

I want this to be explicit. At src/domain/app/index.ts we need to have an
explicit ExtendedAppDTO composed of other DTO objects. Then in src/core we still
need to return non-DTO objects, but both the cli UI and the web-api should
output DTO objects. Then the web-ui should read the DTO object and parse it into
a non-DTO object.

The DTO objects should be inside src/domain. The DTO objects should be next to
their original counter part. For parsing and mapping to DTO object we will have
two functions: parseDTO, mapToDTO. Each of these one will accepts multiple type
in the input and be recursive. Something like

    type DTOs = ExtendedAppDTO | AppDTO | LocalStatusDTO
    type NonDTOs = ExtendedApp | App | LocalStatus
        
    const parseDTO = (dto: DTOs) NonDTOs {
        ...
    }

    const mapToDTO = (nonDTO: NonDTOs) DTOs {
        ...
    }
    
, which should go under src/domain/dtos.ts. At src/domain/dtos.test.ts we should
have appropiate tests.

Then in web-api and CLI we will use mapToDTO and in web-ui we will use parseDTO.
In these cases is ok to use `as` keyword. For example doing
    mapToDTO(await appStatuses.getExtendedApps(...)) as ExtendedAppDTO[]
in cli and web-api, or doing
    parseDTO(/* parse response of GET /apps */) as ExtendedApp[]
in web-ui

